According to **RFC2616 - 9.5 POST**:

> Responses to this method are not cacheable, unless the response includes appropriate Cache-Control or Expires header fields.

However OkHttp does not respect this. See `Cache.put(response: Response)`:

```
    val requestMethod = response.request.method

    if (HttpMethod.invalidatesCache(response.request.method)) {
      try {
        remove(response.request)
      } catch (_: IOException) {
        // The cache cannot be written.
      }
      return null
    }
```

With a request/response like this one, the cache entry should not be removed and should even be updated so that a future GET request can take advantage of it:

```
>>> POST /foobar
{ "baz": true }
```

```
<<< 200 OK
Cache-Control: max-age=900
{ "baz": true }
```

I have a spring-boot Controller, like this:

```java
@GetMapping("/test/{param}")
public String test(@PathVariable String param){
    logger.info("param: {}", param);
    TimeUtil.SECOND.sleep(10);
    return "ok";
}
```

and then I write a test case:
```java
for(int i = 0; i < 20; i++){
    Request req =  client.newCall(request).enqueue(new Callback() {
      @Override public void onFailure(Call call, IOException e) {
         // some code
      }

      @Override public void onResponse(Call call, Response response) throws IOException {
       // some code
      }
    });
}
```

I think there will be 20 request to the controller at one time , but not. Only 6 request arrived at one time , after 10 seconds , other 6 request arrived.

Is this the right answer? 

